A. Connolly provides a provocative analysis of public health and family welfare through the lens of the tuberculosis preventorium. This unique facility was intended to prevent TB in indigent children from families labeled irresponsible or at risk for developing the disease. Yet, it also held deeply rooted assumptions about class, race, and ethnicity. Connolly goes further to explain how the child-saving themes embedded in the preventorium movement continue to shape children's health care delivery and family policy in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChildrenxHospitalsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aChildrenxHospitalszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTuberculosis in childrenxPreventionxHistoryxUnited States. 0aTuberculosis in childrenzUnited StatesxPreventionxHistory. 0aTuberculosisxHospitalsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aTuberculosisxHospitalszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354594340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813545943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813545943.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK